	<article class="post-16033 post type-post status-publish hentry category-featured-posts tag-boehner-john-a tag-lew-jack tag-national-debt-us per-boehner-john-a per-lew-jack des-national-debt-us" id="post-16033">
	<header class="postHeader">
				<div class="postKicker">
					</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">The Embarrassing Debt Ceiling Ritual</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By David Firestone			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-02-04T14:45:56+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">February 4, 2014 9:45 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">February 4, 2014 9:45 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//takingnote.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/02/04/the-embarrassing-debt-ceiling-ritual/" data-title="The Embarrassing Debt Ceiling Ritual" data-description="The Treasury secretary notified Congress that the country&#039;s running out of money, again.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div>
<div class="w480"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/04/opinion/242014lew/242014lew-blog480.jpg" id="100000002687447" width="480" height="299" alt="Jack Lew spoke about Congress raising the debt limit on Feb. 3, 2014.&nbsp;" /><span class="credit">Saul Loeb/Agence France-Presse â Getty Images</span><span class="caption">Jack Lew spoke about Congress raising the debt limit on Feb. 3, 2014.&nbsp;</span></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Jack Lew, the Treasury secretary, must be tired of this embarrassing ritual by now. Every few months, he has to notify Congress that the entirely unnecessary borrowing limit that lawmakers have insisted on imposing must be raised yet again. Then he has to wait while Republicans contort themselves to keep the government out of default while trying to persuade the hard right that they really hate doing so.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It happened <a href="//online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702303942404579360594025818068?mod=WSJ_hp_LEFTWhatsNewsCollection">again Monday morning</a>. In a speech to the Bipartisan Policy Center, Mr. Lew reminded Congress that the last reprieve from default madness expires on Friday, after which the Treasury will have only a few days of cash-shuffling before it runs out of money. The situation is particularly dire this month, he said, because the government has to begin sending out tax refunds and thus draws down its cash faster.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âGiven these realities,â he said, âitâs imperative that Congress move right away to increase our borrowing authority. It would be a mistake to wait until the 11th hour to get this done. As House Speaker John Boehner has said, not only should the United States never default on its debt, we should &#8212; and I quote &#8212; we shouldn&#8217;t even get close to it. The fact is, simply delaying action on the debt limit can cause harm to our economy, rattle financial markets and hurt taxpayers.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Boehner for years encouraged these standoffs, but now seems to understand that they are pointless and cannot be won. After President Obama announced that he would no longer negotiate over the debt ceiling, the speaker essentially caved the last two times, getting nothing of substance in exchange for keeping the country out of default. He has denounced the Tea Party groups that live for these fights, and there have been some recent signs &#8212; a spending bill, a farm bill and a set of immigration principles &#8212; that the Republican majority in the House is struggling to break free of the dead weight on the right that is pulling down the partyâs national image.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">So Mr. Lewâs challenge represents a pretty clear test of whether the House leadership is serious about getting back to governing. Naturally, House conservatives want something in exchange for their approval of a higher ceiling &#8212; approval of the Keystone oil pipeline, changes to the Affordable Care Act or <a href="//washingtonexaminer.com/house-gop-in-a-bind-on-debt-ceiling/article/2543246">some other unspecified measures to reduce the debt</a>. All of them were under discussion at a House Republican retreat last month.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Boehner should have told them not to bother &#8212; the White House isnât going to negotiate. And maybe he did say that, and was ignored, as always, by the deep-end faction of his party that considers him a softie and a sellout. That faction doesnât care that <a href="//www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/wonkblog/wp/2013/10/30/congratulations-america-your-deficit-fell-37-percent-in-2013/">the deficit is actually falling</a>, sharply, or that the last standoff (resulting in the October shutdown) was disastrous for the party. Like Civil War re-enactors, they live only for the sounds of battle, and arenât interested in an outcome that is pre-ordained.</p>
	</div>
